Choosing CPU Vs GPU in Productivity:

Video Production(Editing)-Premiere Pro:
Video rendering primarily relies on the CPU, while the GPU can be utilized as an accelerator. When building a PC for video editing, it is advisable to incorporate a GPU with a capable video transcoding engine. Therefore, opting for the latest generation GPUs with advanced video transcoding engines is highly recommended.

Offline Rendering-3DSMAX, MAYA, Blender:
Offline rendering depends on the rendering engines. Most renderers, such as Maxon renderers, utilize the CPU. On the other hand, engines like Octane and Redshift rely on the GPU. Therefore, the choice between GPU and CPU depends on the specific renderer being used.

Realtime rendering-Unreal, Lumion:
Real-time rendering is highly GPU intensive, so it is advisable to allocate a significant portion of your budget towards the GPU rather than other items.

text:
MostIntel's 8th Gen "H" processors have dual and more than dual core but not quad core(e.g Hexa Cores).
Intel:-
K = unlocked multiplier(OverClockable)
H = high performance graphics
HQ = Quad Core High performance graphics 
HK = Quad Core High performance graphics(OverClockable)
Q = quad core
E = Energy Efficient
U = Ultra Low Power
Y = Extremely Low Power
E = ECC memory(xeon line-up (mostly))
M = Mobile(Laptop or Compact)
N = Notebook
T = Low Power LGA
P = no integrated graphics
G = RX Vega graphics
R = High-End mobile,
C = unlocked
X = HEDT platform(more cores & Clock)
XE = Xtreme Edition
AMD:-
X=OverClock Efficient(more clock cycles)
G=AMD APU(with in-Built Vega Graphics)
WX= Higher TDP(ThreadRipper)
